Observation Details: Found by Don Pye today.

If I had to spend all my days watching the magpie clan at Big John's Cleaners, I would never get bored. Today, I watched them taking turns bathing. There were 7 birds in the flock, with 1 an apparent sentinel. It stayed high up in a tree off to the east a ways; I conjecture that it was looking for danger--or rival magpie clans.  The 6 other birds took turns bathing. See especially the 5 videos, below.   Video 1. That was pretty typical. One bird would bathe for ~15 seconds, before either announcing its turn was over or being nudged out by another.  Video 2. This magpie completes its turn, hops out of the pool, then seems to say, "Next?"  Video 3. A magpie is bathing, then another walks in and the first one moves on. Pretty peaceful, all things considered. (I conjecture that the magpie clans here--there are several--are family groups.)  Video 4. Sometimes 2 at a time (but I never saw more than 2) would bathe together. These two are besties, and their names are Snowball and Madonna.  Video 5. And then this would happen! Under the shade of Proto's, but just a couple meters away from the pool where they were bathing. Not sure I can interpret this behavior: Is this bird eating snow? Is it snow-bathing? Just goofing around? I'm not sure, but I saw this behavior from all the birds (except for the presumptive sentinel), I believe, at one time or another.

If I had to spend all my days watching the magpie clan at Big John's Cleaners, I would never get bored. Today, I watched them taking turns bathing. There were 7 birds in the flock, with 1 an apparent sentinel. It stayed high up in a tree off to the east a ways; I conjecture that it was looking for danger--or rival magpie clans.  The 6 other birds took turns bathing. See especially the 5 videos, below.   Video 1. That was pretty typical. One bird would bathe for ~15 seconds, before either announcing its turn was over or being nudged out by another.  Video 2. This magpie completes its turn, hops out of the pool, then seems to say, "Next?"  Video 3. A magpie is bathing, then another walks in and the first one moves on. Pretty peaceful, all things considered. (I conjecture that the magpie clans here--there are several--are family groups.)  Video 4. Sometimes 2 at a time (but I never saw more than 2) would bathe together. These two are besties, and their names are Snowball and Madonna.  Video 5. And then this would happen! Under the shade of Proto's, but just a couple meters away from the pool where they were bathing. Not sure I can interpret this behavior: Is this bird eating snow? Is it snow-bathing? Just goofing around? I'm not sure, but I saw this behavior from all the birds (except for the presumptive sentinel), I believe, at one time or another.

Yes, THREE! Incredibly unexpected. 3 together near boat landing and within 0.25 mi in either direction for several hours throughout morning. Silent and undetectable at times, very vocal and easy to hear and see at others. Sometimes along road, more often on NW side. Pics and audio to come later but unmistakable ID with white bellies, white wing patches in flight, irridescent greenish gloss to black parts of plumage, very long tail, smaller than crow, and chattery vocalizations closer to CAJA than AMCR. Very rare in WI any time of year and to find 3 may be unprecedented, at least in recent history.

On March 8, Mike Moynihan saw 2 separate BBMA flying along the NE edge of Rondeau Bay. The next day, March 9, David Barr found one near the Eagle’s nest on Fargo Rd and then he found it on March 13 in the field beside the above location.   This morning, RIc and Anne McArthur saw and photographed 2 here. When I arrived, David was there and we watched the pair in the adjacent field, on the front lawn and feeding under the hanging bird feeder. They appear to be building a nest at the top of the spruce tree up near the house. They were constantly carrying small sticks, dead leaves and plant material up to that tree and then returning to the lawn or the field.   At this point, it’s hard to say where these birds have come from. Are they the 2 adults that nested in Elgin County last year? Are they wild? Escaped? Is this the early beginning of a movement of the species into Southern Ontario? We may never know. Maybe there will be some answers in the next few years.   At this point, much like the other recent sightings in southern Ontario, it is best to give these a “Provisional” designation. If we discover more in the future, that designation can be changed. Unfortunately, species deemed provisional count towards lists, unlike exotics.  So technically, I guess this is a new county species. I’m not sure that makes sense but that’s the way it is. Record photos attached.

Observation Details: Relocated the Sunday bird downstream from the campground around 1315,  it was initially calling, then it was found in adjacent mid-canopy riparian trees. Got some cellphone pics, then all went mad, as it strafed Lauren, then Lauren held out her arm, and the bird landed on her arm, hopped up on her shoulder, over the back of her neck, bit Lauren's finger (drew blood), Lauren screamed at it, the bird stared back at Lauren, I suggested that Lauren put on her face mask to protect her eyes/nose/face, and Lauren baby talked to the bird as I took pics. Lauren wanted to go swim & asked what she should do, I wanted to tell Tom Leskiw we had the bird. Lauren shooed the bird off her shoulder and went for a downstream swim. The bird followed Lauren a ways, then disappeared. We heard it a couple times in the early evening.

The Black-billed Magpie is a rare and local Arizona specialty, and is currently known to only be found at Teec Nos Pos in extreme northeastern Arizona, especially near and along Teec Nos Pos Wash. It was the first bird we found as well pulled up to the wash at 7:07 A.M. just after pulling off of the 160 Highway. The wash runs along both sides of the 160 north and south. The bird flew from the wash and across the highway to the north side of the 160. It was joined by another Magpie, and two more then came with the high possibility of another Magpie coming in also. The fifth possible bird was obstructed but that is the impression of the bird that I highly got (fairly large, very long tail, etc.). After observing this group of four, who continued to move north of the 160 along the Wash, we then headed down the known section of the wash, south of the 160 (this marked hotspot). We started to immediately hear more Black-billed Magpies down the wash, and after covering a fairly short distance, we found four more of them close together in walking about a quarter mile. During this time, the Magpies were highly vocal wherever they would go. We carefully listened for any birds flying over head, especially those traveling southward. Once the Magpies who went on the north side of the 160 and went in the north direction, we didn't observe them coming back south again in the short duration in which we observed the Magpies. We felt that at least eight birds was an accurate count, with the possibility of more.

Observation Details: Together, Foraging, Flying, Vocalizing

Yes, THREE! Incredibly unexpected. 3 together near boat landing and within 0.25 mi in either direction for several hours throughout morning. Silent and undetectable at times, very vocal and easy to hear and see at others. Sometimes along road, more often on NW side. Pics and audio to come later but unmistakable ID with white bellies, white wing patches in flight, irridescent greenish gloss to black parts of plumage, very long tail, smaller than crow, and chattery vocalizations closer to CAJA than AMCR. Very rare in WI any time of year and to find 3 may be unprecedented, at least in recent history.

Observation Details: The Magpie flew to the top pitch of the dining hall roof, perched there and looked around the general area from this great vantage point. Observation Details: Exact count

A small social group of Magpies was hanging out together near the dining hall and the hillside below it. I frequently saw the Magpies in the spruce trees in this area as well as below the hill towards the cross country ski chalet.  However at this time, one of the Magpies was sitting on the prime corner spot of the dining hall roof, and then the crow came and challenged the Magpie for the spot. Then the Magpie came back with this challenge posture and scared the crow away. In one of the photos, you can see the Magpie looking down from the roof at the ground where the crow was walking. The two birds were definitley watching each other, and challenging each other for this territory.

I think the video is of a 5th bird. But I'm not positive of any of the preceding; there is much variation in these flocks, but there is also much overlap.

Observation Details: This is a continuing bird in this neighborhood. Frequently associated with crows, but mostly flying around independently. Very aggressive, when first spotted on a light post with two crows, it abruptly jumped on the back of one of them and rode it all the way to the ground. Oddly, neither bird made a sound, nor did any of the other crows pay much attention. The magpie is being fed in the backyard of the second house from the end of Willow, came immediately down to collect the food when it was put out. Photos.

Continuing family group; at least 4 birds seen; they were located across the farmer's field in distant trees, with increasing heat shimmer making photography difficult; after a while two birds worked their way closer along the treeline, giving brief but much closer views; unmistakeable black and white corvids with long tails with occasional flashes of blue-green iridescence on the wings and tail when the light was favourable; photos.

It was pouring rain when we arrived. The Black-billed Magpies were taking shelter in the trees that bordered the soybean field. Soon the rain stopped and 5 were seen together foraging along edge of field. Two adults, 3 juveniles. Large black, white and blue birds with very long graduated tails, white scapulars and white in the primaries.
Single flock, hanging around in alpine for third consecutive day - unusual.

Preening & foraging and some young begging behaviours.. Mobs.

These birds seem to be as common in the Denver area as Blue Jays are in the eastern states. I found them fascinating and beautiful. No matter how many I saw over the week, I was always delighted to see another one.

The Black-billed Magpie is a rare and local Arizona specialty, and is currently known to only be found at Teec Nos Pos in extreme northeastern Arizona, especially near and along Teec Nos Pos Wash. It was the first bird we found as well pulled up to the wash at 7:07 A.M. just after pulling off of the 160 Highway. The wash runs along both sides of the 160 north and south. The bird flew from the wash and across the highway to the north side of the 160. It was joined by another Magpie, and two more then came with the high possibility of another Magpie coming in also. The fifth possible bird was obstructed but that is the impression of the bird that I highly got (fairly large, very long tail, etc.). After observing this group of four, who continued to move north of the 160 along the Wash, we then headed down the known section of the wash, south of the 160 (this marked hotspot). We started to immediately hear more Black-billed Magpies down the wash, and after covering a fairly short distance, we found four more of them close together in walking about a quarter mile. During this time, the Magpies were highly vocal wherever they would go. We carefully listened for any birds flying over head, especially those traveling southward. Once the Magpies who went on the north side of the 160 and went in the north direction, we didn't observe them coming back south again in the short duration in which we observed the Magpies. We felt that at least eight birds was an accurate count, with the possibility of more.
Y'know, you could build a bird festival around this species. It could be the state bird, too. It is absolutely one of THE birds of the Yampa Valley--and of the whole state of Colorado.
